title: Digest: IFL releases 2016 schedule
text:
Digest: IFL releases 2016 schedule Argus Leader Staff 11:09 p.m. CDT October 6, 2015 CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
The Indoor Football League unveiled its 2016 regular season schedule. The 18-week, 96-game slate kicks off on Feb. 26. 
Opening weekend of the 2016 schedule kicks off with a doubleheader when the five-time defending United Bowl Champion Sioux Falls Storm take on the Minnesota Axemen and the Iowa Barnstormers host an old rival in the Green Bay Blizzard. 
Following its season opener against the Axemen, the Storm will play three straight road games, with its byes coming in Weeks 3 (Mar. 11) and 5 (Mar. 25). Following that road-heavy start, Sioux Falls has three of its next four at home. Other highlights from the 16-game schedule include a June 4 tilt with Nebraska, a rematch of last year’s United Bowl Championship game. The Storm will close out the season on the road against the Minnesota Havok on June 25. USF cracks Top 5 in AFCA Coaches DII Poll 
For the first time in school history, Sioux Falls (5-0) is ranked in the top five of the AFCA Division II Coaches Poll. The Cougars, fresh off a 59-10 road win over Wayne State, moved up from No. 7 to No. 5. 
USF is one of two NSIC teams in the top five teams, joining No. 1 Minnesota State. West Georgia, Northwest Missouri, Ferris St. and the Cougars round out the top five. The rest of the Top 25 had a shake-up with the fifth, sixth and ninth ranked teams losing. Delta St. fell from No. 5 to No. 17, Angelo St. tumbled from No. 6 to No. 16 and Valdosta St. dropped 12 spots to 21. 
USF is also ranked in the Top 10 of the D2Football.com Poll, checking in at No. 4. It’s the sixth straight week in the Top 10 for the Cougars, who host Winona State (3-2) on homecoming at 6 p.m. on Saturday. Augie soccer holds at No. 20 
Augustana soccer stays at No. 20 in this week’s National Soccer Coaches Association of America NCAA Division II Top 25. 
Gannon takes the top spot, followed by North Georgia, Western Washington, Grand Valley St., and Angelo St. Northern Sun Intercollegiate Conference opponent Minnesota State moves up four spots to No. 6. 
Augie knocked off Bemidji State 1-0 on Saturday, then went on to win 2-1 in dramatic fashion against Minnesota Crookston. 
The Vikings will be on the road this weekend battling NSIC opponents St. Cloud State on Friday at 7 p.m. and Minnesota Duluth at 1 p.m. on Sunday. Tuesday scoreboard: Class AA soccer finals set; Class AA and A Tournaments wrap up Augie XC in Top 5 
Augie men’s cross country stayed at No. 1 in the United States Track & Field and Cross Country Coaches Association Regional Central Region rankings, and the women's team held at No.2 in the Central, trailing Minnesota Duluth. 
Augustana was off last week and will travel to Sioux City, Iowa this weekend to compete in the Briar Cliff Invitational. Jacks finish second at Chip-N Club Invitational 
LINCOLN, Neb. – South Dakota St.’s women’s golf team shot an 890 (295-299-296) to finish second at the Chip-N Club Invitational at the 6,105-yard, par-72 Country Club of Lincoln course. Notre Dame won the invitational, shooting a four-under par 860. 
Megan Mingo led SDSU, firing a 218 to finish in a tie for sixth. Classmate Hallie Getz finished 16th, shooting a 224. Natcha Srimaneerungroj tied for 19th (227). 
South Dakota’s Brenna Lervick finished at 4-over par and placed 12th to pace the Coyotes, who finished in 12th at the event. 
The Jackrabbits return to action Oct. 12-13 at the Payne Stewart Memorial in Springfield, Mo., while USD heads to the Creighton Classic on Oct. 19-20. USD finishes fourth at Zach Johnson Invite 
DES MOINES, Iowa – South Dakota senior golfer Jordan Rykal backed up his win last week in Illinois with a third-place finish at Drake’s Zach Johnson Invitational at Glen Oaks Country Club. 
Rykal was in 27th place following an opening round 77 (+6). He carded four birdies against one bogey in round two for a 3-under 68 and shot even par during his final round Tuesday to climb into third place. It was his fourth top-five finish in his last two seasons. 
Rykal finished four strokes back of Bradley’s Drake Bushong, who earned medalist honors with a score of 1-under. 
Northern Iowa, behind two top-four finishers, scored a seven-stroke victory against Bradley to win the team title. The Panthers shot 874 for 22-over. Oral Roberts was one stroke behind Bradley in third place at 30-over. South Dakota placed fourth at 35-over. 
USD wraps up its fall season Oct. 25-27 with Old Dominion’s Kilmarlic Invitational in Powells Points, N.C. Pro day wraps up SDSU baseball fall season 
Augie ends first two rounds of NSIC Championships in sixth 
LAKE CITY, Minn. – Augie men's golf completed the second round of the Northern Sun Intercollegiate Conference Championship, shooting a 22-over-par 295. The Vikings ended the first two rounds of the Championship shooting a 604 (36-over). 
The highlight of the second round came from sophomore Parker Klitzke who made a hole-in-one on the par-3, 200 yard 11th hole. Klitzke led the Vikings shooting a 1-over-par 72 and is shooting 5-over 147 for the first two rounds of the Championship event. He is tied for seventh. 
Minnesota State leads the 10-team field after two rounds with a 15-over-par 583. It is followed by Winona State (589), St. Cloud State (596), Upper Iowa (602). Bemidji State rounds out the top-5 after shooting a two round total of 603. 
The first two rounds of the championship were played at the par-71, 6,669-yard The Jewel in lake City, Minn. while the final two rounds will be played in Smithville, Mo. at the Paradise Pointe Golf Complex April 9-10, 2016. Read or Share this story: http://argusne.ws/1LgBOSE TOP VIDEOS
